Exploratory Analysis for Wine from the Vinho Verde Region

The dataset describes the parameters of 1599 red wine varieties produced in the Vinho Verde region of Portugal. The parameters do not identify the specific grape, product, or price, but rather the makeup of the wines, such as: acidities, sugars, sulfates, alcohol, etc.

There are 11 Predictors and 1 Response

  • Quality: Response A discrete quality rating, determined from peoples opinions, on a 0 to 10 scale.

  • Alcohol: Ethyl Alcohol by volume (ABV), expressed as a percentage. It is produced by the fermentation of yeast, sugars, and starches.

  • Residual Sugar: The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation, which will determine if a wine is dry or sweet.

  • Chlorides: The amount of chloride salts present in wine. This is environmental, so wines from the same region may have the same amount of chlorides.

  • Free Sulfur Dioxide: The free form of SO2 that prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

  • Total Sulfur Dioxide: The amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine.

  • Sulphates: A wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, which acts as an antimicrobial and

  • Density: The liquid density, dependent on the percent alcohol and sugar content.

  • Fixed Acidity: The predominant fixed acids found in wines are tartaric, malic, citric, and succinic. Acidity affects taste; wines lacking in acid are flat.

  • Volatile Acidity: The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

  • Citric Acid: Found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines.

  • pH: Describes the level of basicity on a scale of 014. Most wines are between 34 on the pH scale. pH affects color, stability to oxidation, and consequently the overall lifespan of a wine.

redwine = read.csv("red_wine_quality.csv")

Summary of Observations

Some things that stand out about the 1599 obserabations in the data set:

  • Quality is our response on a scale from 0 to 10, but our data set includes values from 3 to 8, where 5.6 is the median. Quality is the only discrete data in the dataset.

  • Other than Quality, all columns contain continuous data.

  • We anticipate outliers in Residual Sugar, which ranges from 0.9 to 15.5, but has a median of only 2.5, Total Sulfur Dioxide, which ranges from 6 and 289, having a median at only 46, and Free Sulfur Dioxide with a range from 1 to 72, and a median of 15.

  • pH is a scale of 0 14, but our dataset ranges from 2.7 to 4.0.

  • Density exhibits an exceedingly narrow range from 0.99007 to 1.00369.

Summary of histograms

  • The response variable, quality, has only a few hundred observations lie outside of 5 or 6. We might consider categorizing the response as <=5 and =>6, in order to have enough observations to support a prediction model.

  • Residual Sugar and Chlorides have the majority of their observations concentrated in one or two bins, so these might not have enough variation to support predicting quality.

  • Density and pH are normally distributed.

  • All other predictors are right skewed: fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid,free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, sulphates, and alcohol.

Each of these four correlations are statistically significant.

library("report")

test <- cor.test(fixed.acidity, citric.acid)
kable(as.data.frame(report(test)))

test <- cor.test(fixed.acidity, density)
kable(as.data.frame(report(test)))

test <- cor.test(free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide)
kable(as.data.frame(report(test)))

test <- cor.test(pH, fixed.acidity)
kable(as.data.frame(report(test)))



Looking at ALL of the variables coefficients and their corresponding p-value

Looking at the p-values for each correlation coefficient, there does appear to some relationship between quality and: 1. fixed.acidity 2. volatile.acidity 3. citric.acid 4. chlorides 5. free.sulfur.dioxide 6. total.sulfur.dioxide 7. density 8. pH 9. sulphates 10. alcohol

**although in many of the cases above the coefficient itself was small (which may indicate that no relationship exists), since the p-value is also small (below alpha=0.05) then this tells us that some relationship may exist. Further analysis will show if the variables above truly influence the response. We did have 1 variable show that no relationship exists with quality according to the high p-value:

No relationship with quality: 1. residual.sugar

Note that there are predictors that appear to possibly have a relationship with other predictors. We will have to look at the VIFs as well as watch for other signs that may indicate multicollinearity.

##Are any of the predictors highly correlated?

variables <- colnames(redwine)

for (i in 1:11)  #first variable comparing
{
  for (j in (i+1):12) #second variable comparing
  {
    print(paste(variables[i],variables[j])) #printing first and second variable that is being compared
    corr <- (cor.test(redwine[,i],redwine[,j])) #cor.test returns correlation coeff with p-value, returns those for corresponding pairs
    print(paste(corr$estimate,corr$p.value)) #print corr estimate and p-value for simplicity
  }
}

Focusing on quality, our target response

No predictors are highly correlated with quality. The predictors in the center are less likely to be useful in our model, because they are the furthest from 1 (perfect positive) and -1 (perfect negative).

par(mfrow=c(1,1), las=3)
barplot(sort(pears_corr[,12], decreasing=TRUE), col="peachpuff", cex.names=0.8, main="Correlation with Quality")

The predictors most strongly correlated with Quality are:

  • alcohol

  • volatile acidity

Other predictors that may influence Quality are:

  • sulphates

  • citric acid

Simple Linear Regression

Because we have no highly correlated predictors with our response variable, we are forgoing simple linear regression modeling, so that we may begin to determine if we can predict the qualilty of wine using the chemical properties of wine.
